itions (Journal of Molecular Evolution, Data: Source 15971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to formic acid (formate)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline pH gradient\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Greigite-catalyzed reduction of CO2 with NH3 to formic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to organic acids is widely supported in hydrothermal settings (Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; Data: Source 2655).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Formic acid + HCN \u2192 acetamide (via reductive amination)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Pyrite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyrite-catalyzed coupling of formic acid with HCN to yield acetamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination enabled by mineral surfaces is a plausible amino acid precursor route (Shock & Schulte, 1990; Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; Data: Sources 2655, 15389).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal conversion of formaldehyde and ammonia to \u03b1-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Magnetite\", \"Greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Magnetite, Greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Serpentinization, reducing environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Magnetite/greigite-catalyzed condensation of formaldehyde and ammonia, followed by carboxylation, forms \u03b1-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal systems can produce \u03b1-keto acids via condensation and redox reactions (Yanagawa & Kobayashi, 1992; Data: Sources 2655, 2626).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Surface mineral contact\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Montmorillonite-catalyzed reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate produces glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination in surface environments is supported for amino acid backbone synthesis (Levine et al., 2008; Data: Source 4643).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate conversion to ornithine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Transamination, non-enzymatic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise transfer of amino group and decarboxylation converts glutamate to ornithine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Non-enzymatic transamination for ornithine synthesis is plausible under prebiotic conditions (Banez & Or\u00f3, 1971; Levine et al., 2008; Data: Source 2655).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of ornithine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Montmorillonite\", \"Phosphate\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Montmorillonite, Phosphate\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Montmorillonite and phosphate-catalyzed Strecker synthesis forms ornithine aminonitrile from formaldehyde, HCN, and NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Strecker synthesis is a widely accepted prebiotic route for aminonitrile intermediates (Levine et al., 2008; Data: Source 4643).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of ornithine aminonitrile to ornithine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitrile intermediate yields ornithine, catalyzed by clay.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolytic conversion of aminonitrile to amino acid is a key Strecker pathway step (Levine et al., 2008; Data: Source 4643).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Guanidinylation of ornithine to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling, mineral contact\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ornithine reacts with guanidine to form arginine under clay-catalyzed and dehydration conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Biochemical guanidinylation is plausible prebiotically; guanidino group formation supported by ammonium cyanide irradiation followed by group transfer (Journal of Molecular Evolution, Levine et al., 2008; Data: Source 15971, 4643).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Histidine pathway: Conversion to ornithine via decarboxylation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling, ambient UV\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Montmorillonite-catalyzed decarboxylation of histidine produces ornithine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Prebiotic conversion of histidine to ornithine is theoretically plausible, connecting routes proposed for amino acid precursors (Levine et al., 2008; Data: Source 21332).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal \u03b1-Ketoglutarate Backbone Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2, NH3, and formaldehyde are converted to \u03b1-ketoglutarate via hydrothermal catalysis; then glutamate and ornithine are formed by surface-phase amination and transamination; ornithine reacts with guanidine to produce arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker Route via Ornithine Aminonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN, formaldehyde, and ammonia undergo Strecker synthesis on clay, producing ornithine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to ornithine and undergoes guanidinylation to yield arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Guanidino Irradiation Route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN and ammonia form ammonium cyanide; UV irradiation yields guanidine, which reacts with ornithine for arginine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Formate-Acetamide Sequence\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced to formic acid and coupled to HCN for acetamide synthesis (hydrothermal/pyrite); acetamide acts as an amino acid precursor, entering surface Strecker or transamination routes.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Histidine Route to Ornithine\",\n      \"description\": \"Histidine formed via surface-catalyzed reactions is decarboxylated to ornithine, which then undergoes guanidinylation to produce arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Hydrothermal Ammonia/Formaldehyde Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct condensation of formaldehyde and ammonia in hydrothermal systems forms \u03b1-ketoglutarate; proceeds to glutamate, ornithine, and arginine via downstream steps.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteorite Delivery and Surface Assembly\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetamide or diamino acids delivered via meteorites (extraterrestrial); they enter Strecker or guanidinylation surface pathways for arginine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal HCN-Driven Backbone Formation\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN, ammonia, and CO2 combine under hydrothermal/greigite catalysis to produce backbone fragments (\u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, ornithine), which are assembled via surface guanidino transfer.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Wet-Dry Guanidino Transfer\",\n      \"description\": \"Wet-dry cycling on clay surfaces concentrates ornithine and guanidine, promoting guanidinylation and arginine formation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfide Hydrothermal Route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN, H2S, and ammonia act under hydrothermal conditions, forming backbone fragments and guanidino precursors; subsequent mineral-catalyzed surface assembly completes arginine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "The network integrates literature-supported plausible routes for prebiotic arginine formation: (1) Strecker-type pathways for amino acid backbone formation, (2) guanidino group assembly via ammonium cyanide irradiation, (3) hydrothermal and surface-catalyzed synthesis of backbone and precursors, and (4) biochemical stepwise assembly and transamination/guanidinylation. The routes combine hydrothermal formation of \u03b1-keto acids and amino acid backbones, surface-phase assembly and polymerization on clays, guanidino group formation via ammonium cyanide irradiation, and environmental interconnection through shared hub intermediates. Most pathway steps are informed by research findings, but full arginine synthesis under prebiotic conditions remains experimental, with acknowledged gaps and speculative connections documented. Multiple convergent routes integrate hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments, leveraging hub molecules including \u03b1-ketoglutarate, ornithine, aminonitrile intermediates, and guanidine.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CN/c1-2", "