 step for closure. Acknowledged gap: see Unresolved Challenges in the Prebiotic Synthesis of Arginine, research summary above.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Indirect guanidine formation via cyanamide hydrolysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV energy input\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven oligomerization and hydration of cyanamide yields guanidine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Journal of Mol. Evol. (1977): Photolytic chemistry of cyanamide as plausible source of guanidine; widely accepted as prebiotic mechanism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide formation from surface ammonium cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Thermal decomposition of ammonium cyanide on clay minerals yields cyanamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Supported by Ferris et al. (1981): Clay-catalyzed conversion of ammonium cyanide to cyanamide.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteorite delivery of ornithine and guanidine, followed by aqueous assembly\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [null],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"Variable (meteorite aqueous alteration, 273-343K)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"low\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Extraterrestrial delivery, possible hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Direct delivery of ornithine/guanidine through meteoritic input enables aqueous assembly of arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Shock & Schulte (1990): Meteorites as plausible prebiotic sources of amino acid precursors. No specific arginine, but ornithine/diamino species observed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Alternative pathway: Reductive amination and chain elongation leading to ornithine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reductive hydrothermal chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C\u2013C bond-formation via hydrothermal carboxylation, followed by amination and chain extension (paralleling stepwise assembly).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Shock & Schulte (1990); Yanagawa & Kobayashi (1992): General C5-C6 aminodicarboxylic acids synthesis supported, though specific ornithine yields are low.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Main Hybrid Strecker-Guanidino Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal/surface Strecker-type backbone assembly (HCN/aldehyde/ammonia) produces ornithine, while surface irradiation of ammonium cyanide yields guanidine; condensation gives arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Glutamate Backbone Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal \u03b1-k